@course

id: book:emotional-design-kvtm
title: Emotional Design
author: Readlock
description: How three layers of feeling decide which objects we love and which we forget.
color: #db2777
genres: design, psychology
relevant_for: designers, product managers, anyone

@segment
Three Layers of Feeling
TLF

@package
The Pretty Machine That Worked Better
Free

@text
Two coffee makers sit on the same kitchen counter.
One is rough plastic. The other is smooth and warm to the touch.
Both pour coffee at the same speed.
So why does the prettier one feel easier to use?

@text
In the 1990s, when ATMs were still a new sight on city streets, researchers ran a small study.
They built two versions of the same machine.
The buttons did the same thing in the same order.
The wiring, the speed, and the menu were all identical.
Only the look changed.
One screen was plain and clunky, the other was clean and balanced.
Then they asked people to try both machines and rate how easy each one felt.

@text
People rated the prettier machine as easier to use, even though both machines were identical inside.
They could not name the difference, but they felt it.
When the same researchers tried the test in another country, the result came back the same.
The look of the machine was reaching into the person who used it.
A pleasant design made the testers more patient with the machine when things went wrong.

@question
Why did the prettier machine feel easier to use?

answer: The buttons on the pretty version were actually faster.
consequence: The two machines were identical on the inside, button by button.

answer: The pleasant look made people more patient and forgiving when something went wrong.
consequence: A pleasant design loosens the mind, which makes small problems feel smaller.

answer: The pretty version had a simpler menu hiding harder steps.
consequence: The menus were the same on both machines, button by button.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: When the body feels good, the brain becomes more flexible and forgiving with mistakes. The same broken button stops feeling broken once the mood lifts.
hint: Both machines were identical inside, so the change was happening somewhere else.

@text
What kept showing up in those trials has a name: <c:g>the aesthetic-usability effect</c:g>.
When something looks pleasant, people find it easier and more forgiving.
The change happens inside the person looking at the screen.
A relaxed, slightly happy brain is better at thinking around small obstacles than a tense one.
So the most useful work a designer can do is sometimes also the most decorative.

@true_false
A frustrated user is better at problem-solving than a relaxed user, because frustration sharpens focus.

true: True, frustration helps focus and improves problem-solving.
consequence: Frustration narrows attention to the immediate problem, which makes creative workarounds harder to find.

false: False, a relaxed mind solves problems more flexibly than a frustrated one.
consequence: Positive feeling broadens thinking, so a relaxed user finds workarounds the frustrated user misses.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Positive affect broadens cognition, while frustration narrows it to the immediate obstacle.
hint: Think about whether stress widens or narrows what the brain can see.

@text
The look of an object reaches into the person using it and changes how the world feels.
That is one of the layers where design touches feeling.
The next layer sits underneath, in the first half-second of seeing something new.

@package
The Half-Second Before Thought

@text
Sometimes a hand reaches for something on a shop shelf.
The body says yes before the mind has weighed anything.
No label has been read, and no spec has been checked.
So what is making the decision before thought has time to arrive?

@text
A child stands in front of a basket of apples at a market stall.
Without checking the price, she reaches for the roundest and shiniest one.
Every apple on the table tastes the same.
None of them is worth more than the next.
The round, shiny one has already been chosen, and the choice happened in less than a second.

@text
A man walks down a long museum hall lined with hundreds of small Greek clay pots.
He has been walking for half an hour, and his feet hurt.
Then his eyes catch one pot, and his body stops.
The pot is smooth and balanced.
The pots around it are slightly off in shape and slightly heavier on one side.
He could not say why this one made him stop, only that it did.

@text
A woman walks along a beach at the end of a long day.
The sand is full of stones, all roughly the same colour.
She is not collecting anything.
Then her hand bends down on its own and picks up one polished, oval stone.
Hours later, she puts the stone on her windowsill and cannot quite explain why she kept it.

@question
What do these three moments have in common?

answer: The people knew exactly what to look for in advance.
consequence: None of the three were following a plan or a checklist.

answer: The choice happened in the body before the mind had time to weigh it.
consequence: Something visual triggered a yes before any conscious thought arrived.

answer: Each person was looking for the cheapest option.
consequence: Price had nothing to do with any of these three moments.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The body reacts to certain shapes and surfaces faster than the conscious mind can catch up.
hint: Notice how fast each decision was made, before any thinking happened.

@pause
A round, polished shape can stop a person in a market or a museum just the same.

@text
The first layer of how design touches the human is called <c:g>the visceral level</c:g>.
It is the part of the brain that fires before any thought.
The signal arrives in the half-second between seeing something and knowing what it is.
Round, smooth, symmetrical, and warm: humans have been wired for these shapes for thousands of generations.
The wiring sits below culture and below language.
A child in a market and a man in a museum are running on the same instincts.

@true_false
Aesthetic preferences are mostly learned from culture, not built into the body.

true: True, all aesthetic taste is shaped by culture.
consequence: Most aesthetic taste is cultural, but the layer underneath is built-in and the same everywhere.

false: False, the visceral layer of preference is built into the body.
consequence: The visceral layer is built into the body and runs the same across very different cultures.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The visceral level of aesthetic response is largely hardwired, while the layers above it are shaped by culture.
hint: Think about what a child and an adult in different cultures both find appealing.

@reflect
A kitchen tool kept for its looks alone: a hand-painted bowl or a pretty mug.
A surface that hands keep touching for no clear reason: a pebble or a handle.
A small item kept on a shelf for no practical reason: a stone or a postcard.

@text
The visceral layer is the half-second jolt, the body reacting before thought arrives.
It is only the start.
A second layer wakes up later, when the object stops being looked at and starts being used.

@package
The Knife That Knew Her Hand

@text
Why do some kitchen tools get used every day while others sit untouched in the drawer?
There is always one favourite knife, one favourite pen, one favourite coffee cup.
The hand keeps coming back to the same one, day after day.
What is it about that one tool that the others lack?

@text
A woman receives a chef's knife as a gift on her thirtieth birthday.
It looks plain compared to the others in her drawer.
The handle is wood, the blade is slightly worn, and the look is nothing special.
The first time she uses it, she notices how the handle fits her palm exactly.
The blade tilts forward when she lifts it, almost as if the knife wants to do the work.
By the end of the meal, the other knives in the drawer have started to feel awkward.

@text
A year passes.
The woman has cooked hundreds of meals with the new knife.
Her hand reaches for it without looking, the way it reaches for a pen.
The other knives sit clean in the back of the drawer.
When she travels, she has to use other knives in friends' kitchens.
Each one feels strange and clumsy in her hand.
What she loves about the knife is how it answers her hand.

@question
What is it about the favourite knife that the others lack?

answer: It looks more expensive than the other knives in the drawer.
consequence: Looks were the visceral layer. This story is about a different part of the brain.

answer: The way it fits the hand and the way it moves during the work.
consequence: The knife rewards the hand on every use, which is why the hand keeps returning.

answer: It was a gift, so the woman feels guilty about not using it.
consequence: The hand keeps choosing the knife because it likes the choice, not from guilt.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A tool that fits the hand rewards the body every time it is picked up.
hint: Notice what part of the body keeps choosing the knife, and why.

@text
<c:g>The behavioral level</c:g> is the second layer of how design touches feeling.
It is what happens during the long minutes of using something, after the half-second of looking.
A tool that fits the hand becomes a small reward every time it is picked up.
The body files away these rewards without the mind noticing.
Over months and years, the favourite tool becomes the one that has rewarded the hand the most often.

@true_false
A favourite tool is usually the one that looked best in the shop.

true: True, the look in the shop is what makes a tool a favourite.
consequence: Looks decide what is bought. Use decides what becomes the favourite.

false: False, what makes a favourite happens after the tool is brought home.
consequence: The favourite is built over months of use, not chosen in the shop window.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The visceral level shapes what gets bought, and the behavioral level shapes what stays in use.
hint: Think about how often the prettiest tool in a kitchen actually gets picked up.

@reflect
A tool the hand keeps choosing, even with newer options nearby: a mug or a pen.
A tool that looked right in the shop and turned out to feel wrong in use.
A small daily friction a better-shaped object would erase: a stiff handle or a sharp edge.

@text
The hand learns the tool, and the tool wins or loses on what it gives the hand.
The visceral and the behavioral layers are now in place.
The third sits above both, in the part of the mind that does not touch the tool, but tells stories about it.

@package
The Watch That Was More Than a Watch

@text
For most of human history, people have decorated their things with marks that did nothing useful.
There were patterns on clay pots, feathers in hats, and names carved into bowls.
The pot still held water and the bowl still held soup.
So why did people spend any time on the marks at all?

@text
A man owns two watches.
Both keep time perfectly, both cost about the same, and both look fine on the wrist.
He almost always wears the second one.
The first watch was bought from a shop.
The second was given to him by his father, a year before his father died.
Asked which watch is better, he would say neither.
Asked which one he would feel terrible about losing, he would name the second without thinking.

@text
A young woman keeps a cracked mug at the back of her cupboard.
The handle is chipped, the glaze is fading, and the inside is stained from years of tea.
She has plenty of newer mugs that look better and pour cleaner.
She bought the cracked mug for herself when she first moved into her own flat.
On the days when life is going badly, she takes the mug down and drinks tea from it.
After holding the mug for a few minutes, the day starts to feel more bearable.

@question
Why do the second watch and the cracked mug matter so much to their owners?

answer: They are objectively better than the alternatives.
consequence: Both pairs of objects are equal in function. The second one wins on something else entirely.

answer: They carry a memory and a story that the alternatives do not.
consequence: An object can carry a piece of someone's history, and that piece becomes part of using it.

answer: They are more expensive than the other options.
consequence: Price has nothing to do with either story.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Some objects become small monuments to a person or moment, and we keep using them long after better versions exist.
hint: Compare the function of each object with what each one means to the person who owns it.

@pause
The objects we cannot throw away are often the cheapest ones we ever owned.

@text
<c:g>The reflective level</c:g> is the third layer of how design touches feeling.
It is the part of the mind that tells the story about owning an object.
A second-hand watch becomes a small monument to a father, and the time it keeps turns secondary.
A cracked mug becomes the marker of a first home, and the tea it pours hardly matters.
Reflective design is the layer where objects become parts of who we are.

@true_false
A favourite object always becomes a favourite because of how well it works at its job.

true: True, function is what makes an object a favourite.
consequence: The deepest favourites are kept for the meaning they carry, even when they no longer work well.

false: False, meaning often matters more than function.
consequence: The deepest favourites are kept for what they mean. The cracked mug is the worst cup in the cupboard.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: An object can become a small monument to a person or a moment, and that monument outlives any newer model.
hint: Think of an object kept long after a better one was available.

@reflect
An object kept at home for no practical reason: a postcard or a small stone.
A gift impossible to replace, even though a perfect copy could be bought tomorrow.
Something carried daily because of the person who chose it: a pen or a key ring.

@text
The third layer is where objects start carrying memories the body alone could not hold.
The visceral, the behavioral, and the reflective are now all in place.
Some of these objects refuse to leave their owners long after the use is gone.

@package
The Shoes That Refused to Leave

@text
Most people know someone who has kept a pair of shoes for years after they fell apart.
The soles are worn through, the laces have been replaced, and the leather is scuffed.
Better shoes sit in the same closet, untouched.
Why does that one pair refuse to go?

@text
In her early twenties, a woman buys a pair of running shoes from a small shop.
They are nothing special, just the cheapest pair the shop had in her size.
She wears them for the first time on the morning she decides to start running.
The first run lasts ten minutes and ends with her bent over a fence, gasping.
Three months later, she runs her first five-kilometre race in them, and finishes crying.

@text
Years pass.
The shoes go with her on hundreds of runs, through rain, heat, and dark mornings before work.
The soles wear through, and the laces fray.
Eventually they sit at the bottom of the closet, falling apart.
By her mid-thirties, she could buy ten better pairs without thinking.
None of the new ones are the shoes she ran her first race in.
She still cannot bring herself to throw the old pair away.

@question
What is keeping the old pair of shoes in the closet?

answer: They still run better than any of the newer pairs.
consequence: The shoes are worn out and unusable. The keeping has nothing to do with running.

answer: They hold the memory of a moment that changed her life.
consequence: The object has become a small monument to the morning she became someone who runs.

answer: They cost more than the newer pairs and would be wasteful to throw away.
consequence: The shoes were the cheapest pair in the shop. Cost is not what is keeping them.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The deepest attachments combine all three layers, but the reflective layer is the one that refuses to let go.
hint: Think about which of the three layers is doing the keeping.

@text
The deepest attachments do not come from one layer alone, but from all three working together.
The visceral catches the eye in the shop.
Years of use teach the hand to keep coming back, which is the behavioral layer.
By the time an object has been part of an important moment, the reflective layer has bound it to that moment for good.
Together, all three form what is sometimes called <c:g>emotional design</c:g>.
It refuses to separate how a thing looks, how it feels, and what it means.

@true_false
The strongest connection a person can have with an object always comes from how well it works.

true: True, the strongest connections are about function.
consequence: Function helps, but the strongest connections also carry memory and meaning the body cannot replace.

false: False, the strongest connections are not about function alone.
consequence: A pair of worn-out shoes can mean more than ten better pairs, because of what they were there for.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The deepest attachments layer function, comfort, and meaning together, with the meaning usually lasting longest.
hint: Compare the function of an object with the role it has played in someone's life.

@reflect
An object too important to throw away, even with a perfect replacement available: an old notebook.
Something with a beautiful look, a satisfying touch, and a memory in it: an old pen.
A replacement that turned out quietly worse than the original: a chair or a knife.

@text
The thread running through this course is that an object is never just an object to the person holding it.
It enters the body, the hand learns to return, and the object slowly carries pieces of a life.
Maybe the harder question is which objects in any home are quietly doing all three at once.
